<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic, Tudjman To Sign Accord 15 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203212594 Paris AFP in English 2118 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203212594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 2 (AFP) -- The final accord creating 
a Bosnian federation of Croats and Moslems will be signed on 
March 15 in Washington, Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic 
said in a television interview here Wednesday [2 March]. 
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic and his Croatian 
counterpart Franjo Tudjman will sign the document, following the 
accord reached Tuesday [1 March], Silajdzic said from Washington. 
  The accord calls for a federation of Bosnian Croats and 
Moslems, comprising a number of cantons. The cantons would have 
equal rights, with a central government in charge of foreign 
affairs, defense and trade. Bosnian Serbs are not included in 
the deal. 
  Silajdzic added that experts from the two sides would in the 
meantime work on a new constitution, both for Bosnia-Herzegovina 
and for a future confederation of the Bosnian and Croatian 
republics. These experts would meet in the U.S. embassies in 
Vienna, he said. Silajdzic said he would shortly travel to 
Moscow. 

</TEXT>

