<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet on Granting Temelin Station Guarantees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0203183594 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1600 
GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0203183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Jitka Kucerova on 2 March cabinet meeting] </F>
  [Text] According to Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus, the 
Cabinet has discussed granting the Exim Bank guarantees for the 
completion of the building of Temelin nuclear power station. 
The Czech side has received a report that this problem was 
discussed yesterday between the Austrian ambassador and the 
president of the bank and some U.S. senators. Vaclav Klaus 
stressed that the government is following all of the activities 
of the Austrian side closely; he said he assumes that Austria's 
negative attitude will not be accepted, and guarantees will be 
dealt with positively in the congressional debate on 10 March. 
  The government also accepted a report on the situation of 
the 
customs union. Vaclav Klaus said: 
  [Begin Klaus recording] The Czech Government is apprehensive 
about the latest development. It is aware of the complexity of 
the situation on the Slovak side. Nevertheless, it interprets 
the debates on certificates, norms, and so on as finer forms of 
protectionism, and we consider this an unfortunate infringement 
of the current practice and style of foreign trade relations. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

