<F P=100> ALBANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia's Tudjman Continues Visit, Activities </TI></H3>
<H4>   Attends Opening of Embassy </H4>
<F P=102> LD0103174394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0103174394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Andjelko Perincic from Tirana] </F>
  [Excerpt] [Perincic] Our embassy was opened in the capital 
of Albania today in a formal ceremony held in the presence of 
Franjo Tudjman, president of the Republic of Croatia. The 
ceremony was attended by the leadership of this friendly 
country: Albania President Sali Berisha, Pjeter Arbnori, 
president of the People's Assembly, and Prime Minister 
Aleksander Meksi. Also present were members of the diplomatic 
corps and many citizens of the host country. 
  Following a speech by Croatian Ambassador in Tirana Mladen 
Jurisic, those present were addressed by Croatian President 
Franjo Tudjman. 
  [Begin Tudjman recording] The opening of the Croatian 
Embassy 
in Tirana marks the beginning of something special in that it is 
the continuation of the (?historical) links between the Croatian 
and Albanian people ever since the Illyrian times. [end 
recording] 
  [Perincic] Let us remember Queen Teuta. The legendary 
Albanian hero, George Kastrioti, is mentioned in Croatian folk 
songs. This is yet more evidence of the links between the two 
peoples. It should not be forgotten, Tudjman went on to add, 
that in the former Yugoslavia under the leadership of Tito, a 
Croat, the Albanians of Kosovo enjoyed all rights, including 
their university and academy. 
  [Begin Tudjman recording] Today, under democratic 
conditions, 
and with the introduction of democratic systems in Croatia and 
Albania, we wish to continue the legacies of history on new 
foundations and in the new situation in which both Albania and 
Croatia need to be the mainstays of the new international order 
in southeast Europe. [end recording] 
  [Perincic] Albanian President Sali Berisha also spoke 
briefly. He expressed the hope that the Croatian Embassy in 
Tirana would serve to enrich cooperation between the two 
countries. He also expressed satisfaction with President 
Tudjman's visit to mark the occasion. He voiced the hope that 
the Croatian and Albanian people will continue to nurture their 
traditionally good relations. In this context he mentioned 
(Milan Suflaj), a Croat expert on Albania, killed at the time of 
the Yugoslav monarchy. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

