<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   BIS Chief Congratulates U.S. on Exposing Ames </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0403112094 Prague CESKY DENIK in Czech 1 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0403112094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CESKY DENIK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "cer": "Devaty Congratulates CIA on Success] </F>
  [Text] Prague--Stanislav Devaty, acting director of Czech 
counterintelligence, BIS, commented yesterday on the case of 
exposed Russian spy Aldrich Ames, otherwise a high-ranking 
official of the U.S. intelligence service, the CIA. 
  Stanislav Devaty told a CESKY DENIK correspondent: "In my 
post, I can only congratulate our U.S. colleagues on their great 
success. I must say that in all the time I have held this 
position, since August 1992, I have not come across a case that 
would be even remotely reminiscent of a CIA employee's 
defection. As a citizen, I am distressed by the confirmation of 
my concerns that even under the new circumstances Russia has not 
changed its approach to the objects of its interest. The head 
of Russian intelligence, Primakov, recently said that the Czech 
Republic's place in Russia's sphere of certain interests does 
not mean that Russia conducts activity against the interest or 
laws of our country. In view of what has happened, I am not 
certain whether this statement of his can be trusted." 

</TEXT>

