<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily Says Harvard Funds Controlled by Kozeny </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0303161294 Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES in Czech 2 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0303161294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague MLADA FRONTA DNES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "(sim, ina)": "Harvard Funds Are a Family </F>
Business Run by Kozeny"] 
  [Text] Viktor Kozeny, as president of Harvard Capital and 
Consulting, represents, within this company, the interests of 
the majority owner of the shares. According to Boris Vostry, 
company vice president for foreign operations, Kozeny can 
directly influence events in the company without having to 
change the members in its supreme bodies and without being a 
member of the board. 
  Even after his resignation from the board, Kozeny remained 
in 
the five-member executive committee, which operatively controls 
Harvard Capital and Consulting. 
  "Harvard is Kozeny's family business, and speculations about 
his position are therefore irrelevant," Vostry said. The fact 
that Viktor Kozeny resigned from the Harvard Capital and 
Consulting board has changed nothing regarding his position of 
majority owner of the firm, Vostry added. Officially, it is 
impossible to precisely verify the property situation in Harvard 
funds because their shares are not tradable, and this 
information is protected by law. According to a source from 
another privatization fund, who did not want his name to be 
revealed because he wanted to avoid possible problems, Kozeny 
owns the majority of the shares, and another part (of the 
company) is controlled by his grandfather, Frantisek Stehlik. 
  Kozeny, he affirms, has resigned from the board for health 
reasons. Ivan Kralik, a former employee of the Presidential 
Office of Husak [Czechoslovak president under the communist 
regime] and a member of the company's board, has been entrusted 
with chairing the board. Kralik also worked at the Castle for a 
certain time after Havel assumed office. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

