<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   New SNS Chairman on `Danger' to Republic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303185094 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0303185094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] I am Slota the terrible! I am the new chairman 
of the Slovak National Party [SNS]! This is how the SNS 
chairman welcomed journalists at the party's regular news 
conference today. [passage omitted] After the news conference, 
Jan Slota spoke to our correspondent Lydia Mrazova. [passage 
omitted] 
  [Begin recording] [Mrazova] Mr. Chairman, in an interview 
for 
the SLOVENSKY NAROD newspaper, you said that your members and 
sympathizers were aware of the danger threatening the Slovak 
Republic. "Danger" is a very serious term that can hide 
anything. What, then, is your interpretation of danger in 
current politics? 
  [Slota] I understand the term "danger" as two distinct 
dangers. On the one hand, as the communist danger, and, on the 
other, as a danger from the south. As regards the former, I 
wish to stress that it would be very dangerous if Slovaks 
supported left-wing parties because, in 1948, this danger was 
also underestimated. Perhaps not so much in Slovakia, but, all 
the same, eventually communism was planted in Slovakia, too, and 
we know very well what sort of time followed, the 1950's and all 
that. So the Slovaks should not forget the past. 
  As regards the latter, the south, well, anyone who does not 
wish to see will not see. But we, SNS members, really do see 
how Slovaks in the south of Slovakia, the very people whose 
state and territory this is, find themselves in a position of an 
ethnic minority. Slovaks are afraid and migrate to the north. 
In a word, they are afraid to assert themselves as Slovaks. 
[passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

