<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Vice President Explains Staff Cutbacks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0403132194 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1000 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0403132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A total of 129 employees of Hungarian Radio have 
been dismissed or pensioned off. According to a statement by 
[Hungarian Radio Vice President] Laszlo Csucs, their names will 
not be published to respect their personal rights. In his 
statement issued by MTI, the vice president supported the idea 
of unbiased public service activity. We quote: 
  The transformation of the system is under way in Hungary and 
Hungarian Radio cannot avoid this either. The State Audit 
Office's investigation, which was carried out in 1992, drew top 
officials' attention to several shortcomings, though it found 
financial matters in order. Hungarian Radio prepared a plan of 
measures that included a plan to reduce overly high staff 
numbers, which stood at over 2,000 people. 
  According to Csucs's statement, decisions on redundancies 
were not based on political, but professional and ethical 
criteria; that is, Hungarian Radio dismissed those who did not 
meet these criteria, the vice president's statement reads. 

</TEXT>

