<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   British UNPROFOR in Ljeskovica Shelled </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0403133394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1200 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0403133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Anton Mrkonjic in Zepce] </F>
  [Excerpt] At 0635 this morning three 82-mm mortars fell on 
the British UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] base in the village 
of Ljeskovica, between Zepce and Zavidovici [central Bosnia, 
around 100 miles northwest of Sarajevo]. British forces 
commander Major Darling informed the command of the 111th HVO 
[Croatian Defense Council] Brigade that their radar equipment 
detected the direction and even the location from where the 
mortars were fired, but declined to say who was responsible for 
the shelling of the British battalion. Fortunately, there were 
no casualties, but material damage is huge. Maj. Darling said 
that if the shelling happens again he would demand air strikes 
against those who fire shells on UNPROFOR. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

