<H3> <TI>   Russians Seen as Tuzla Protectors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303234694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2019 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0303234694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 3 (TANJUG) -- Col. Momir Zec of the 
Bosnian Serb Army assessed that the decision to allow opening of 
the Tuzla Airfield "was a good move by the military and 
political leadership" of the Bosnian Serb state, the Republic of 
Serbia (R.S.) [in Bosnia-Herzegovina], as "the announced NATO 
threats were being removed" in this way. 
  The Russian forces, which will control the airfield at this 
northeastern Bosnian town under Moslem control, will prevent its 
possible abuse, said Col. Zec to the R.S. news agency SRNA 
Thursday. 
  The accord on opening the airfield at Tuzla was [word 
indistinct] Tuesday during the talks of R.S. President Radovan 
Karadzic with Russian ranking officials in Moscow. 
  The Bosnian Serbs accepted for the Tuzla airfield to be 
opened for humanitarian aid on condition Russian monitors carry 
out control as the Serb side feared the airfield could be used 
for bringing in arms and military equipment to the Bosnian 
Moslems. 
  U.N. Undersecretary for Peace Operations Kofi Annan said 
recently that the U.N. planned the opening of the Tuzla 
airfield for March 7 in an operation which could involve also 
NATO air support, while French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe 
recently threatned the Bosnian Serbs with air strikes if they 
prevented the opening of the airfield. 

</TEXT>

