<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Remain Cautious </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303172194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1413 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0303172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 3 (TANJUG) -- Serb military sources 
in eastern Bosnia welcomed the decision of Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic to open Tuzla airport and Russian guarantees 
that its observers would monitor the airport. 
  The commander of the Serb forces in the territories east of 
Tuzla, Colonel Momir Zec, has said that the Serb forces, 
regardless of the agreement which allows humanitarian flights to 
Tuzla, are keeping a close watch on the airport. 
  Col. Zec Told Belgrade daily POLITIKA that the top Serb 
military officials were not surprized by the decision to re-open 
the Tuzla airport. 
  "This is a political move which removes the NATO threats 
and, 
within such a compromise, it suits us better to have Russian 
troops supervize the airport," Col. Zec explained. 
  The whole issue of the Tuzla airport has been discussed by 
the media for the past seven months, the Colonel recalls. It is 
an artificial, extremely politicized construction, allegedly 
aimed at facilitating the supply of relief aid. it is obvious 
that some Western countries want to neutralize the arms embargo 
resolution on Bosnia and use the airport to supply the Bosnian 
Moslems with arms. 
  The Tuzla airport is 5-6 km away from Serb front lines, Col. 
Zec said. it is in poor condition. The runway, which was 
damaged, is being repaired, but not the airport buildings. 
  Colonel Zec also denied some agency allegations that the 
Bosnian Serbs bombarded Tuzla 3 days ago, immediately after the 
downing of the four aircraft near Banjaluka. "We do not bombard 
Tuzla. We only respond to Moslem provocations, but our actions 
are aimed strictly at military targets," Colonel Zec said. 
  Since the beginning of the war, two years ago, there have 
never been large-scale battles between the Serbs and Moslems in 
and around Tuzla. 14,000 Serbs still remain in the town, but 
the Moslem authorities refuse to allow them to leave. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

