<H3> <TI>   Weapons To Be Collected </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0403145794 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1400 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0403145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Croat and Muslim forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina have 
agreed to allow Unprofor forces to begin patrolling demarcation 
lines as of tomorrow, Commander Rob Anning, UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Force] spokesman in Sarajevo said today. 
  The agreement was reached in Gornji Vakuf today between 
representatives of the Bosnia-Herzegovina army led by General 
Muslimovic, and the Croat Defense Council led by General Vrbant, 
Anning said. 
  Talks on the opening of six roads crossing the front lines 
are due to start at the same time. These measures should enable 
the implementation of the general cease-fire agreement and the 
collection of weapons, which should come into effect at 1200 on 
7 March. Weapons are to be collected in five or six locations 
under UN supervision. 

</TEXT>

