<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Not To Renew UNPROFOR Mandate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303175494 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0303175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Croatian President Franjo Tudjman today received 
Yasushi Akashi, the UN secretary general's special envoy and 
UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] coordinator for former 
Yugoslavia, and his associates, the president's office announced. 
  Recalling that the UNPROFOR mandate [in Croatia] was 
expiring 
at the end of this month, Tudjman said Croatia would not agree 
to renew the mandate under present conditions. He emphasized 
that UNPROFOR supervision in the protected areas was 
insufficient, the best proof of which was the latest incident 
involving the downing of Serb aircraft which took off from 
protected areas in the Republic of Croatia. Special Envoy 
Akashi said the UN secretary general would inform the Security 
Council about the implementation of UNPROFOR's mandate in 
Croatia by the end of the month. 
  Speaking about the Croat-Muslim Washington agreement, 
President Tudjman said the entire geopolitical situation has 
changed as a result of this and international and Croatian 
efforts would now be directed towards the solving of the problem 
of the reintegration of protected areas into the constitutional 
and legal system of the country. 
  In conclusion, President Tudjman stressed that the problem 
no 
longer lies in the territorial settlement between the three 
nations in Bosnia-Herzegovina, but that a division between East 
and West has now surfaced, whose interests have always clashed 
in this area, the president's office has announced. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8090 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu043_k_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-043 </AU>
