<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPO: Muslim-Croat Agreement `Revised Yalta' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0403115194 Belgrade BORBA in Serbo-Croatian 3 Mar 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU0403115194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade BORBA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Legalization of Revised Yalta"] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade -- Yesterday's Croatian-Muslim agreement, 
backed by the United States and the powerful Western states, 
presents in its essence the division of the former Yugoslavia 
into the Western and Russian sphere of interests. That 
agreement, if it succeeds, will represent an international 
legalization of a somewhat revised oral agreement reached half a 
century ago in Yalta among Stalin, Roosevelt, and Churchill. 
This is said in the statement by the Serbian Renewal Movement 
[SPO] Presidency. 
  Slovenia, Croatia, and about half the territory of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina will be under the political and economic 
patronage of the most developed countries in the world, while 
Serbia, Montenegro, and the Srpska republic will be in the 
sphere of the political influence of Russia. It will be a region 
that will not be in the position to count on the economic and 
technological support by the West for a long time, the SPO says. 
  As for the republic of Serbian Krajina, its fate will be 
decided through negotiations between Zagreb, which is becoming 
increasingly strong economically, and Knin, which on the other 
hand is economically weakening. 
  The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia will most likely 
find itself with Greece and Albania under the political and 
economic influence of the West, the SPO Presidency says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

