<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yugoslav Radio Ship Stops Broadcasting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303182894 Hilversum Radio Netherlands in English 1150 GMT 
3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0303182894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hilversum Radio Netherlands </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the weekly "Media Network" feature] </F>
  [Excerpts] [passage omitted] The radio ship broadcasting 
off the coast of Yugoslavia, known as Radio Brod, went off the 
air on Tuesday at midnight. The station had been broadcasting 
to all of the former Yugoslavia since April of last year. The 
European Union, which had been backing the project, said it 
could no longer provide financial support because of an 
administrative reorganization. The journalists from throughout 
the former Yugoslavia who were involved in the project are 
understandably furious. At a press conference on Tuesday they 
said the weren't given any warning about the move and therefore 
couldn't look for alternative financing. 
  The journalists have asked Italy for authorization to set up 
a transmitter off the Italian coast. Italy, they say, is their 
last hope because the republics of the former Yugoslavia have 
all refused to allow them to erect a transmitter and the 
Albanian government hasn't responded. [passage omitted] 
  The ship is now sailing to Marseille in the south of France 
and the 19 journalists on board all plan to return home -- 
except for the three Bosnians, who have no home to return to. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

