<H3> <TI>   UN Official Praises Tuzla Airport Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0303100294 Warsaw PAP in English 1846 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0303100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Mar. 2 -- According to Tadeusz Mazowiecki, 
the Serb announced opening of the airport in Tuzla "is very 
important to the region." Mazowiecki has insisted on the 
importance of this event for quite some time in his reports. 
The opening of the airport defended by the Muslims in Tuzla in 
Bosnia was announced by Radovan Karadzic, leader of the Bosnian 
Serbs in Moscow on Tuesday. 
  Mazowiecki, special rapporteur of the UN human rights 
commission on the observance of human rights in the former 
Yugoslavia, returned to Warsaw from Geneva on Wednesday, where 
he had presented his report on Monday. 
  The conflict entered a new phase from the moment that the 
heavy divisions left Sarajevo in result of the pressure exerted 
by the UN secretary general and NATO, emphasized Mazowiecki, 
adding that for the first time the international community has 
put its words into action. "This is why we can hope that peace 
in this region is possible," he concluded. 

