<H3> <TI>   Justice Minister Assesses Visit to Greece </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203171494 Sofia BTA in English 1535 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, March 2 (BTA) -- Bulgarian Minister of 
Justice Petur Kornazhev expressed his satisfaction with his 
three-day formal visit to Greece paid at the invitation of Greek 
Minister of Justice Yeoryios Skouvelakis. 
  PASOK's [Panhellenic Socialist Movement] Cabinet stands 
firmly in favour of closer contacts with Bulgaria, Mr. Kornazhev 
told a BTA reporter upon his return to Bulgaria. He also said 
that Greece is expecting a visit by Bulgarian Prime Minister 
Lyuben Berov in a two week's time. 
  Mr. Kornazhev told this reporter that he and his host 
identified a common understanding on the judicial problems of 
the European Union. The two discussed a variety of issues, 
including the conditions in Bulgarian and Greek jails, problems 
pertaining to the execution of death penalty and the specificity 
of the Balkans. 
  Mr. Kornazhev and Mr. Skouvelakis reportedly considered a 
bilateral agreement on transfer of convicts which has to be 
further deliberated before being signed. 
  Speaking with his Greek hosts, Mr. Kornazhev stressed that 
Bulgaria is supportive of a policy of active neutrality in the 
Balkans and that it sees no controversial issues concerning its 
borders with Greece. The Bulgarian minister of justice said he 
also met Greek Interior Minister Akis Tsokhatzopoulos. 

</TEXT>

