<F P=101> Caech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Formal Recognition of FYROM Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0303192394 Prague CTK in English 1826 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0303192394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Skopje March 3 (CTK) -- With the exchange of notes 
between the Foreign Ministries here today the mutual recognition 
and establishment of diplomatic relations between the Czech 
Republic and Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM], the former Yugoslav federation republic, 
was formally endorsed. 
  The Czech Government already officially recognised Macedonia 
and announced its intention to set up diplomatic relations on 
ambassadorial level on March 2. In fact, the Czech Republic has 
practically recognised Macedonia by voting for its acceptance 
into the United Nations. 
  The note was extended to the Macedonian side today by 
Director of the Czech Foreign Ministry Euro-Atlantic Division 
Ivan Busniak. He also handed his Macedonian colleagues a 
message from Czech President Vaclav Havel, Premier Vaclav Klaus 
and Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec. 
  Macedonia won independence two years ago after the breakup 
of 
the former Yugoslavia. It was practically the only Yugoslav 
republic which gained independence in a peaceful way. The 
position of Greece, which objects to the use by Macedonia of the 
name "Macedonia" and the state symbols which are considered by 
Greeks as their historical heritage prevents more rapid 
international recognition of Macedonia. 
  "Given that the Czech Republic has resorted to this step 
under a certain concrete situation existing in the Balkans and 
especially in the southern part of the region, its decision to 
establish diplomatic relations with Macedonia is a recognition 
of the balanced, sober and realistic politics of the current 
Macedonian leadership," Busniak said. 
  At the same time, he noted that the decision was not taking 
sides in the dispute between Macedonia and Greece, which has 
been going on for over two years. That is why the Czech 
Republic recognised Macedonia as the "former Yugoslav republic" 
and at the same time the Czech Government stated that it 
recognised Macedonia in its current borders. 
  It is impossible to expect opening of embassies in Prague 
and 
Skopje in the near future primarily due to economic reasons, he 
said. 
  "We are really greatly interested in opening an embassy in 
Prague. However we are building our diplomatic service 
practically from scratch and we have neither sufficient 
financial means nor necessary cadres," Macedonian Foreign 
Minister Stevo Crvenkovski said, adding that his country was 
able to open 25 representative offices abroad at the most. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

