<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Caech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Reacts to NATO Air Attack in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203084294 Prague CTK in English 2203 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203084294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 1 (CTK) -- "I think NATO felt the 
need to show firmness," Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus said in an 
interview broadcast by Czech Radio on Tuesday concerning 
Monday's shooting down by NATO of four Serbian planes. 
  Klaus stressed that until this morning it was not clear 
which 
planes had been involved. "We know well that in this strange war 
many strange things are done by individuals which are not 
entirely synchronized and coordinated with the others," he said. 
  In Bosnia there were now various "subcommanders who have the 
power to send out four planes somewhere," Klaus said. 
"Therefore I think I am right in saying that not even the NATO 
commander was clear -- he said so this morning -- as to where 
the planes left from and why they were going somewhere," Klaus 
said, adding that "something happened, and it is unnecessary to 
speculate about what it will lead to." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

