<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Approves Defense Doctrine Bill </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203092894 Prague CTK in English 2149 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 1 (CTK) -- The Slovak Government 
on Tuesday approved a proposed defense doctrine allowing for a 
reasonably-sized army which corresponds to the need for a 
rational deterrent in the national interest. 
  "Slovakia does not feel immediately threatened, but in the 
current military-political situation preserves the right and the 
ability to defend itself against possible military and 
non-military attack," the text of the doctrine reads. 
  The Slovak Republic wishes to promote its interests by 
peaceful cooperation with all democratic countries, with 
emphasis on neighboring countries, the doctrine continues. The 
aim of this cooperation is to form a European security system 
without military confrontation. The doctrine also confirms the 
interest of Slovakia in entering NATO and the Western European 
Union, and claims the right to share in the activities of the UN 
as a guarantee of peace and security. 
  The document contains an undertaking to strictly conform to 
the limits established by international agreements concerning 
the number of soldiers and the main types of weapons, and to aim 
at reduction in these respects. 
  The proposal also allows for the civil control of military 
power by parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

