<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar Defends Decision on Privatization Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203091594 Prague CTK in English 2300 GMT 1 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203091594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 1 (CTK) -- It is inadmissible for 
the only disposable resources from privatization to be in the 
hands of the National Property Fund (FNM) and for responsibility 
for the smooth running of the state to be transferred to the 
government, Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar said in a Slovak 
television debate on Tuesday evening. Meciar was justifying his 
decision not to sign the law on large privatization, which will 
be returned to parliament. 
  He said the law on large privatization had to ensure the 
connection between the FNM and the government, although it was 
not necessary that the finance minister be also chairman of the 
Inspection Body of the FNM. It was in the interest of 
parliament that a member of the government, possibly a state 
secretary, should be a member of the FNM board, Meciar said. 
  As well as being premier, Meciar is at present privatization 
minister and chairman of the FNM board. However, the amendment 
to the law on privatization forbids this. 
  If the government is not connected to the FNM, which will 
also be the holder of the disposable resources, the cabinet will 
not be capable of giving companies further guarantees for loans 
and credits abroad, because it will not be able to cover 
possible losses, Meciar warned. 
  "If we knew what sort of situation we might get into we 
would 
propose a state budget without a deficit. The deficit we would 
shift on to the FNM, as Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus has done," 
Meciar said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

