<H3> <TI>   SDL Official on Observation of Rights Pledges </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0203145394 Prague CTK in English 1336 GMT 2 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0203145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague March 2 (CTK) -- The Committee for Legal 
Affairs and Human Rights of the CE (Council of Europe) said that 
Slovakia was no longer observing the pledges it had assumed when 
it was accepted into Council of Europe, Robert Fico, a leader of 
the opposition Democratic Left Party (SDL), told Slovak Radio 
today. 
  Most criticism regarded the "roadsign bill" on bilingual 
names of communities, parliament did not pass, as well as the an 
amended bill on names and surnames requiring the Slovak suffix 
-ova for Hungarian female names, said Fico who represented 
Slovakia on Tuesday's [1 March] meeting of the CE Committee. 
  "The law is good, but its interpretation is disputable," 
Fico 
said, adding that "the atmosphere in the Committee was 
orientated unequivocally against Slovakia." 
  The controversial issue of referendum on the loss of 
mandates 
of the deputies who quit their parties was not officially 
raised, Fico reported. There was, however, certain fear "at 
least" at the unofficial level of the CE. 
  The bilingual roadsigns and use of Hungarian names and 
surnames are the most frequent demands of ethnic Hungarians 
which are supported even by Slovak President Michal Kovac. 

</TEXT>

