<F P=101> The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   PDP Decries Lack of Government Representation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0303121294 Tirana ATA in English 1119 GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0303121294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tirana, March 3 (ATA) -- About 40 per cent of the 
population in the former republic of Macedonia [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] is of Albanian 
nationality. Nevertheless, since the independence, this state 
has functioned as a national state of the Macedonian people, 
says a letter of the (Macedonian) People's Democratic Party 
[PDP] addressed to the CSCE Council of Ministers recently. 
  The Macedonian Constitution and many other laws have thus 
discriminated against the Albanian people especially in the 
fields of education, culture, and citizenship, the letter 
stresses. The Law on Nationality in Macedonia has declared some 
100,000 Albanians as persons without nationality. 
  The government in Macedonia is in general centralized while 
local governments do not exist. The central government is made 
up almost wholly of ethnic Macedonians with the occasional 
symbolic Albanian, although there are some 300 Albanian jurists 
looking for work in Macedonia. Non-representation of the 
Albanians in the structures of the present government is 
justified by the government as being inherited from the past, 
the letter says, but this is not convincing because new 
institutions, such as diplomacy, are being set up on the basis 
of nationalities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

