<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Yugoslavia, Kosovo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Give Academy to Deaf-Mute Association </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0103190194 Tirana ATA in English 1114 GMT 28 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0103190194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prishtina, February 28 (ATA) -- The building of the 
Academy of Arts and Sciences of Kosova, which this week was 
usurped and closed by the Serbian police, is given now to the 
Deaf-Mute People Association of Kosova, reports the Serbian 
means of information, referring to the installed Serbian 
governor of Kosova, Mr. Milosh Simovic, who says that "the 
academy has been tolerated enough because the decision for its 
abolishment has been taken since two years ago." 
  The Academy of Arts and Sciences of Kosova has been 
established since sixteenth years ago according to a decision of 
the Kosova Assembly, during the time when Kosova was an 
autonomous region. 
  "The academy is of Kosova and it will exist and act as the 
highest institution of science, art and culture in Kosova" is 
stressed in the many reactions done against the Serbian attacks 
over the academy. 
  The Kosovar Academy of Helsinki, expressing his indignation 
to the closing of the building of the academy and appealing and 
asking help from the international institutions, stresses that 
"the usurpation of the building of the academy is a signal that 
shows that the Serbian authorities with premeditation want to 
abet the inter-ethnic conflict in Kosova, which will have 
unforeseen consequences not only for the Albanians of Kosova, 
but even for all the Balkan region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

