<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatian Official on Draft Constitution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0603230194 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2100 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0603230194 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] A transitional committee made up of delegations 
of the Republic of Croatia and Muslims and Croats from 
Bosnia-Herzegovina continued its work today at the U.S. Embassy 
in Vienna. Ivo Sanader, Croatian deputy minister of foreign 
affairs, has spoken to our reporter Sandra Posum Djurin. This 
is how Deputy Minister Sanader views the transitional 
committee's work: 
  [Begin Sanader recording] I would describe our work so far 
as 
good. We are making progress. For the time being there are no 
major problems. There is a fair deal of adjusting positions. 
It is perhaps interesting to mention that at the moment we are 
working on the first item, the first set of issues, namely the 
constitution of the future federation of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
between Croats and Bosniak Muslims. I believe that today or 
tomorrow, perhaps tomorrow, we may finalize a draft constitution. 
  Afterward, the preliminary confederation agreement follows 
between the federation and the Republic of Croatia. This is 
then followed by a military agreement on military organization 
within the federation. 
  The fourth item includes transitional measures for speeding 
up the founding of the federation and the confederation; 
wherever it is possible, this will include state organization as 
well. 
  These are the three sets of issues that remain to be 
resolved 
once we have finished working on the federation constitution. 
You know that for our part we have decided -- these have always 
been our propositions -- that the Muslims and Croats in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina should seek reconciliation, that an end 
should be put to all their conflicts. 
  We find continuity in our policy along these lines. The fact 
that the world's greatest democratic power has become heavily 
involved in these talks testifies in practical terms to the fact 
that we have always followed the right and correct path. Now 
this transitional committee of ours is tasked with a very 
difficult and responsible duty, I would even say an historic 
task, of outlining what Minister Granic, Prime Minister 
Silajdzic, and President of Herceg-Bosna Zubak signed in 
Washington in the presence of U.S. Secretary of State 
Christopher in such a way as to make both sides satisfied, first 
in the federation, and to find a mutual interest in the future 
confederation. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

