<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Spokesman Views Croat-Muslim Federation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0603172294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1702 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0603172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Budapest, March 6 (TANJUG)--Although agreements 
conducive to peace should be welcomed, the recently signed 
agreement on a Croat-Muslim federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina has 
parts which indicate that what is actually involved is the 
creation of a military bloc against the Bosnian Serbs, Army of 
Yugoslavia (V.J.) spokesman, Col. Ljubodrag Stojadinovic warned 
on Sunday. 
  Col. Stojadinovic said on a Hungarian radio programme that 
the Bosnian Serbs had no reason why to join the "inconceivable 
Croat-Muslim federation," which the V.J. spokesman said would 
not last long. 
  Col. Stojadinovic said that the setting up of the federation 
would mark a step backwards, that is, a return to how things 
were when war broke out in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The war broke out in 1992 after the Muslim-Croat coalition 
took a decision on the forcible secession of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
from the then Yugoslav Federation against the wishes of the 
Bosnian Serbs and contrary to the republican Constitution which 
specified that all vital decisions required the consensus of all 
three peoples in the republic. 
  The Serbs in Bosnia-Herzegovina proclaimed the Serb Republic 
(R.S.) in 1992 on their historical and ethnic territories. 
  Col. Stojadinovic said that it was the duty of the V.J. to 
defend the territory and air space of the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia and, at the same time, carefully to follow what was 
taking place in the immediate neighbourhood, particularly where 
the Serb people lives. 
  The spokesman said that the V.J. expected the crisis in 
Bosnia- Herzegovina to be resolved peacefully, but was ready for 
the worst, although it felt that the R.S. and neighbouring 
republic of Serb Krajina (RSK), the Serb state within the 
administrative boundaries of the former Yugoslav Republic of 
Croatia, could alone defend themselves. 
  Col. Stojadinovic repeated the official V.J. statement that 
the four planes downed over Bosnia-Herzegovina early in the week 
were not part of its air force and that no V.J. pilots were at 
the time in the area where NATO fighter-bombers had taken action. 
  The incident is quite mysterious, since it occurred in an 
area where the Bosnia Muslims and Croats are engaged in mutual 
fighting, Col. Stojadinovic said. He said that NATO 
representatives should provide the answer to the question whose 
the downed planes were. 
  Col. Stojadinovic said there would be no danger if the 
airfield near Tuzla, in north-eastern Bosnia-Herzegovina, was to 
be used strictly for humanitarian purposes, but specified that 
there would be a real danger if the airfield was to be opened by 
force. 
  The Bosnian Serbs and Russia reached an agreement in the 
middle of the week for Russian observers to check all deliveries 
arriving at the Muslim-held airfield near Tuzla. 
  The Serb side has insisted on the control of the air 
deliveries out of fear that the airfield could be used for 
illegal munitions shipments to the Bosnian Muslims. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

