<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Foreign Ministry Criticizes Walesa </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0403195094 Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network in 
Polish 1830 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0403195094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Relayed by Warsaw TV Polonia Network] </F>
  [Text] [Announcer] The Russian Foreign Ministry has 
protested against statements made recently by Lech Walesa 
regarding the excessive concentration of Russian troops in the 
Kaliningrad area. 
  The Ministry's representative, Mikhail Demurin, declared 
that 
what the Polish president had said during his visit to Latvia 
was not conducive to stability in the Baltic region and was an 
affront to the spirit of Polish-Russian agreements. 
  On 24 February, during an official visit to Latvia, 
President 
Lech Walesa said that the excessive concentration of Russian 
troops in the Kaliningrad district was not beneficial to 
security in the Baltic region. 
  [Reporter] The Kaliningrad district belongs to Russia, and 
everything that happens there is an internal matter for the 
Russian Federation, said Deputy Foreign Minister Sergey Krylov, 
commenting on Lech Walesa's statement. 
  The spokesman of the Russian Foreign Ministry, Mikhail 
Demurin, added that Russia had the right to keep within the 
Kaliningrad district as many troops as was necessary to ensure 
security. According to Deputy Minister Krylov, President Walesa 
is well aware that many Russian soldiers are in the district 
temporarily. This situation arose when troops were withdrawn 
from the Baltic countries, and it was impossible to relocate 
them in other regions of the country. 
  The Russian diplomat believes that by his statement Lech 
Walesa wanted to please the Latvians. According to experts, 
there are at present 150,000-200,000 Russian soldiers stationed 
in the Kaliningrad district. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

