<H3> <TI>   Slovak Political Right Parties Merge </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0503210394 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0503210394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Two hundred delegates of the Conservative 
Democratic Party-Democratic Party [KDS-DS] held their 
constitutional congress in Bratislava today. Their aim was to 
finalize the merger of these two nonparliamentary parties of the 
political right. Correspondent Oto Goerner interviewed Pavol 
Hagyari, the newly elected chairman of the party. 
  [Begin recording] [Hagyari] The constitutional congress 
decided the name of the new party. Three names were proposed: 
the Democratic Party; Conservative Democratic Party-Democratic 
Party, a double-barrelled name; and the Party of the Democratic 
Right. The first proposal was given a clear majority, which 
means that, as of today, we are to be called the "Democratic 
Party." I am convinced a new, strong party of the right is 
being created, which in the last elections attracted 10 percent 
of the voters. We are convinced the same will be the case at 
the next elections that may be held very soon. 
  [Goerner] Is it not a paradox that there are some parties 
splitting in the present climate while the KDS and the DS merge? 
  [Hagyari] It is also a question of political foresight. If 
the Civic Right failed in the last elections because it was 
split, if we can learn from our own mistakes and from the 
mistakes of the Polish right, then we are left only with merging 
into one political spectrum with more right-of-center 
nonparliamentary parties. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

