<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting Between Army, Serbs in Krajina </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0603190094 Paris AFP in English 1803 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0603190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, March 6 (AFP) -- A weekend artillery duel 
between Croatian Army troops and breakaway Serbs in the Krajina 
region left a woman dead and several people wounded, news 
reports and the United Nations said. 
  The official Croatian news agency HINA said the shelling 
broke out late Saturday and continued into Sunday morning. The 
UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) confirmed the fighting but not 
the casualty report. 
  Shelling in the Gospic area of southern Croatia increased 
Sunday with UN troops counting 87 Croatian Army shells to 80 
fired by Serb forces. One shell landed 20 metres (yards) from a 
positions held by Czech UN troops, while two mortar shells fell 
between 100 and 200 metres (yards) from another Czech post, 
UNPROFOR said. The Czechs had reported sporadic shelling in the 
area late Saturday. 
  The fighting comes a week after both sides extended to March 
31 a Christmas ceasefire. Until now the truce had been 
respected in three of four zones controlled by secessionist 
Serbs and monitored by UN troops. 
  The truce has been violated on numerous occasions, mainly 
around the strategic Maslenica bridge, the only route linking 
Zagreb with the heavily populated Dalmatian coastline in 
southern Croatia. 
  Croatian Serbs seized the Krajina region in the civil war 
that broke out in 1991 when Zagreb declared independence from 
Serb-dominated Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

