<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNPROFOR Controls Airport </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703134494 Paris AFP in English 1339 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0703134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tuzla, Bosnia, March 7 (AFP) -- Swedish and Danish 
soldiers of the United Nations Protection Force (UNPROFOR) took 
over control Monday of the airport of Tuzla in northern Bosnia 
from Bosnian government troops. 
  They were to start preparing the airport for the reception 
of 
humanitarian aid flights following a weekend agreement by 
besieging Serbs to allow two air corridors into Tuzla. 
  Some 100 Swedish troops backed by armoured vehicles, 
including six Danish-crewed Leopard tanks, entered the base at 
1:30 p.m. (1230 GMT) to replace the last elements of the 
mainly-Moslem Bosnian army. 
  Earlier half-a-dozen Moslem trucks had left the airport 
carrying troops, documents and other equipment. 
  The 2,400 metre (3,000 yard) runways, which can take heavy 
transport aircraft, are within range of Serb artillery, but the 
airport has not been shelled since last week. 

</TEXT>

