<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rose, Army Chief on Muslim-Croat Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0503164694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0503164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Army General Rasim Delic, chief of the general staff 
of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army, and Gen. Michael Rose, UNPROFOR 
[UN Protection Forces] Commander for Bosnia-Herzegovina, had 
talks in Sarajevo today. The two commanders discussed the 
dynamism of the implementation of the cease-fire agreement, 
signed between the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and the HVO [Croatian 
Defense Council] transition from a war to a peace situation in 
the city of Sarajevo, as well as possibilities of UN 
representatives entering Maglaj. 
  Gen. Rose was optimistic in assessing the activity so far in 
the realization of the HVO-Bosnia-Herzegovina Army agreement, 
which he could see for himself during his visits to Old Vitez, 
Gornji Vakuf, and other parts of central Bosnia in the past few 
days. He pointed out the problems of implementing the agreement 
in the city of Sarajevo, where he expects a great deal of work 
in the near future. The Army and civil authorities are expected 
to make their contribution to this in cooperation with the 
UNPROFOR. 
  Army Gen. Delic said that Bosnia-Herzegovina Army units and 
commands were ready to carry out all the tasks laid down by the 
peace agreement with the HVO. The agreement is being 
implemented with success on the ground and there is room for 
optimism, said Army Gen. Delic. 
  As for the opening of Dubrave airport near Tuzla, the stands 
of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and the state leadership are 
quite clear. We insist that the airport be opened, but I do not 
accept any Serb conditions regarding its opening. This is our 
free territory and there can be no discussion about the 
territory, which our army has liberated, stressed Army Gen. 
Delic at the end of the talks today. 

</TEXT>

