<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Under Muslim Mortar Attacks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0503141594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1318 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0503141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Sarajevo, March 5 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Moslem forces 
launched mortar attacks on Serb settlements and army positions 
around Sarajevo in the night between Friday and Saturday despite 
a cease-fire which came into force on February 10, the Bosnian 
Serb Army said in a statement. 
  On Friday and on Saturday, the Moslems opened cannon, 
mortar, 
anti-aircraft and small arms fire on Serb settlements and army 
positions in the areas of Doboj, Teslic, Maglaj and Mt. Ozren in 
northern Bosnia, the statement added. 
  It also said that regular troops of the Republic of Croatia 
had not withdrawn from Bosnia-Herzegovina although the deadline 
set by the U.N. Security Council expired on February 17. 
  On February 3, the Security Council threatened to introduce 
sanctions against Croatia unless it withdrew its regular troops 
from Bosnia. 
  From the outset of the Bosnian war nearly two years ago, the 
Croatian Army supported the local Croat and Moslem forces in 
their war against local Serbs. Since early 1993, however, 
Croatia's regular troops and Bosnian Croat forces have been 
fighting pitched battles with Bosnian Moslems for territories in 
central and southern Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

