<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Deny Bombing Maglaj </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0603194294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1911 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0603194294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 6 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serb aircraft 
did not bomb Moslem-held Maglaj on Sunday morning, Bosnian Serb 
military sources said. 
  The Moslem forces which control this northern Bosnian town 
are burning piles of tyres to make it look as if the town is in 
smoke after an air raid, the sources said. 
  Moslem-controlled Radio Sarajevo alleged on Sunday that 
Bosnian Serb aircraft had destroyed the bridge across the River 
Bosna which bisects Maglaj, and Moslem army commander Gen. Rasim 
Delic has requested the commander of the U.N. Protection Force 
in Bosnia, General Sir Michael Rose, to order "an immediate 
intervention" by the NATO air force. 
  The NATO Command for Southern Europe in Naples, Italy, on 
Sunday denied that Bosnian Serb aircraft had violated the "no 
fly" zone over Bosnia. 
  NATO Spokesman in Naples John Jeffrey said NATO had no 
information about any violation of Bosnian air space and could 
not confirm that Maglaj had been raided from the air. 
  REUTERS, Mega and Antenne 1 television crews have filmed 
Moslem assaults on the eastern slopes of Mt Ozren and the 
situation in nearby Maglaj, and the footage showed the town to 
be quiet. 
  Bosnian Serb military sources said that the Moslem 
allegation 
of a Serb raid on Maglaj was designed to draw attention away 
from Moslem offensives in the north -- in the areas of Mt Ozren, 
Trebava and Doboj, and in the Bosna river valley. 
  The Bosnian Serb army said in a statement that a Moslem 
sabotage unit from Tesanj had blown up the iron bridge in Maglaj 
in order to prevent Moslem civilians from crossing to the right 
bank of the Bosna and fleeing to Moslem-held Zenica in central 
Bosnia, under an agreement with the Bosnian Serb army. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

