<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Breach of Flight Ban Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0603152694 Paris AFP in English 1319 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0603152694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, March 6 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb 
warplanes twice attacked the northern Moslem enclave of Maglaj 
on Sunday [6 March], Radio Sarajevo reported, but NATO officials 
in Italy said they had no reports of a UN flight ban over Bosnia 
being breached. [passage omitted] 
  In Naples, a spokesman for the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organisation denied the Bosnia "no-fly" order had been breached 
Sunday [6 March]. U.S. Major John Jeffrey said the Western 
military alliance had received no reports of an attack on 
Maglaj. Any breach of the flight ban would have led to a NATO 
riposte, he said. An Italian spokesman for NATO told AFP: "As 
far as we are concerned nothing happened." 
  Maglaj, whose pre-war population of 19,000 was 45 percent 
Moslem, has been besieged by the Serbs for eight months and its 
residents are said to be living in appalling conditions. Sadic 
said that 11 people were killed and 24 others recently when the 
town's hospital was shelled. 

</TEXT>

