<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Evacuations of Wounded From Mostar Begin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0503151894 Paris AFP in English 1443 GMT 5 mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0503151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, March 5 (AFP) -- Thirty-two wounded were 
evacuated Saturday [5 March] from the besieged Moslem sector of 
the southern Bosnia-Herzegovina city of Mostar on Saturday, 
witnesses said. 
  The wounded and some 47 family members were taken to Citluk, 
around 20 kilometres (12 miles) south of Mostar, in Spanish UN 
Protection Force vehicles, before being flown to the Croatian 
port of Split on British helicopters, said journalists. 
  They were due to be flown to the Italian military base of 
Ancona where they are to be taken to a transit centre before 
flying on to hospitals in Britain, Denmark, Italy, Spain, the 
United States and the United Arab Emirates. 
  The evacuation comes after a ceasefire between the 
Moslem-dominated Bosnian army and Bosnian Croat forces came into 
effect February 25. 
  Some 55,000 Moslems are holed up in the shattered remains of 
eastern Mostar, battered by 11 months of shelling from Croat 
forces camped in the western districts of the historic city. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

