<H3> <TI>   Bulgaria's President Zhelev Offers Help </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0303175594 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1700 
GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0303175594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiro Gligorov, president of Macedonia [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia --FYROM], on 3 March received 
Bulgarian Deputy Foreign Minister Dimitur Ikonomov, who paid a 
brief working visit to Skopje. Our correspondent in Skopje 
Kostadin Filipov reports. 
  [Begin Filipov recording] Dimitur Ikonomov conveyed to Mr. 
Gligorov a message from Bulgarian President Zhelyu Zhelev, which 
was in response to a letter that the Macedonian head of state 
sent to Dr. Zhelev a week ago. 
  In his message to the Macedonian president, Dr. Zhelyu 
Zhelev 
expressed Bulgaria's willingness to further develop its friendly 
and goodneighborly relations with the Republic of Macedonia in 
all spheres -- economy, trade, culture, and so on -- on a 
constructive and principled basis. 
  Against the background of the complex political situation in 
this part of the Balkan peninsula, this is an expression of 
Bulgaria's willingness to help the Republic of Macedonia 
overcome the difficulties related to the tense relations between 
Macedonia and Greece. 
  The specific issues will apparently be specified at a later 
date by the appropriate organs and institutions of the two 
neighboring states. 
  This should by no means be interpreted as Bulgaria 
relinquishing its principled position of refusing to upset the 
balance of its relations with all states in the Balkan political 
space and supporting every step aimed at strengthening regional 
peace and stability. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

