<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Planes Stage `Air Show' Over Towns </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0603173794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0603173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The residents of Vitez, Travnik, Novi Travnik, and 
other towns in central Bosnia watched a kind of air show today. 
At 1612, two Super-Galeb aircraft of the former Yugoslav 
People's Army appeared in the sky above central Bosnia. 
Choosing their targets, they obviously wanted to demonstrate 
the planes' capabilities and the pilots' skills. Judging by 
appearances, the aircraft were only a bait for NATO planes 
because they did not engage in combat activity. So as not to be 
hit by ground weapons, one aircraft released protective flares 
over Vitez. The exhibition by Serb pilots ended at 1635, when 
NATO planes appeared flying at a very high altitude. The Serb 
Galebs gained height and flew away toward their home base, 
accompanied by whistles of many people who watched the display 
and obviously did not understand the aim of such a show of force. 

</TEXT>

