<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs, UNPROFOR Agree on Tuzla Corridors </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0603180394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1727 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0603180394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 6 (TANJUG) -- The Bosnian Serb 
Republic (R.S.) and the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) on 
Sunday agreed on the opening of two air corridors to Tuzla, a 
Muslim-held town in the north-eastern part of the former 
Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The agreement was reached at Pale, the R.S. administrative 
centre, between R.S. president Radovan Karadzic, special U.N. 
Secretary-General's envoy for the former Yugoslavia Yasushi 
Akashi, and UNPROFOR Commander for Bosnia-Herzegovina, Gen. 
Michael Rose, the R.S. news agency SRNA said. 
  Akashi confirmed after the meeting that an agreement had 
been 
reached on the opening of two air corridors which would link 
Tuzla with Croatia's capital of Zagreb and the Croatian Adriatic 
port of Split. Akashi said that the ways and means of securing 
the airfield near Tuzla had also been agreed. 
  The Japanese diplomat said that Karadzic had guaranteed the 
safe use of the airfield, but there remained some difficulties 
with the other two sides, the Bosnian Muslims and Croats, with 
whom he said no agreement had been reached yet. 
  A group of Russian experts left for Tuzla on Sunday to carry 
out preparations for the opening of the airfield in line with an 
agreement reached between the Russian Government and the R.S. 
  Russian observers will check all deliveries which arrive at 
the Dubrava airfield near Tuzla, because the Serb side fears the 
airfield could be used for illegal munitions shipments to the 
Bosnian Muslims. 
  Karadzic said after the meeting with the two UNPROFOR 
officials that he was satisfied since "things are moving in a 
positive direction and confidence is also gradually increasing." 
  The R.S. president set out special interest in the "free 
movement of civilians in Sarajevo, since arounds 60,000 Serbs 
are still to be found in the Muslim section of the city, where 
they are held as ethnic hostages." Karadzic recalled that an 
agreement had been reached at the Geneva peace talks on the free 
movement of civilians between the Serb and Muslim sections of 
Sarajevo. 
  Asked to comment the statements of Bosnian Muslim leaders 
that peace could be reached in Bosnia-Herzegovina in April if 
the Serbs were to join the Croat-Muslim agreement on a 
federation, Karadzic said that "peace is possible even earlier." 
He, however, said he doubted the new coalition's readiness to 
accept a peaceful solution to the conflict. 
  Karadzic recalled that Muslims and Croats had been "hostile 
towards Serbs" in both the first and second world wars, just as 
he said they were now. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

