<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peterle Hails Croat-Muslim Federation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0403170294 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1430 GMT 4 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0403170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Foreign Minister Lojze Peterle at today's news 
conference spoke about some most important events of the last 
few days and about the meeting of the foreign ministers of the 
Central European Initiative, which will start in Trieste today. 
Igor Juric reports: 
  [Begin Juric recording] Minister Peterle first expressed 
satisfaction that NATO had accepted the Slovene request for 
integration into the Partnership for Peace. Slovenia will sign 
the agreement as the first among the countries that did not have 
the right to automatic membership in the agreement. 
  Minister Peterle and Prime Minister Drnovsek are expected to 
sign a document on cooperation between Slovenia and NATO at NATO 
Headquarters on 14 or 15 March. 
  In the continuation of the conference, Minister Peterle 
hailed the signing of the agreement between the Croats and the 
Muslims in Washington. He said that he had received a letter 
from U.S. Secretary of State Christopher yesterday, who thanked 
our country for assistance in the resolution of the crisis in 
the Balkans and informed us about the end of the negotiations. 
Minister Peterle sent a reply to him today. 
  With the Hungarian ambassador, Lojze Peterle exchanged a 
ratifying charter on friendly cooperation between the two 
countries. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

