<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-045 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNPROFOR Controls Tuzla Airport </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803160594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0803160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Enes Osmancevic from Tuzla] </F>
  [Text] Early this morning units of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army left the area of Dubrave [Tuzla] Airport and at 1300 Tuzla 
airport was officially handed over to the UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR]. This was done by signing an agreement between the 
representatives of our republican authorities and UNPROFOR, that 
is to say, UN officials. 
  Although members of the Nordic Battalion took over control 
of 
Tuzla airport yesterday, UNPROFOR will be officially accountable 
for the safety of the airport, which has been under its control 
for several hours, as of today. 
  To recap, approximately 300 soldiers of the Nordic Battalion 
took up positions to secure the airport in the course of 
yesterday. Six Leopard tanks are positioned in the vicinity of 
the runway, which have the authority to protect this airport by 
force if need be, that is to say, to respond to possible fire 
from the Serbian aggressor's positions with fire. 
  It is worth mentioning once again that the runway has been 
ready to receive aircraft for over 18 months. We have learned 
unofficially that as of today all other preparations to make 
Tuzla airport operational have been accelerated. 
  Official forecasts say that this should happen on 18 March; 
however, sources close to UNPROFOR anticipate that it might 
happen before this date. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

