<H3> <TI>   Croats Protest Inaction on Weapon Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0703220894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2100 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0703220894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Zdenko Vranjes] </F>
  [Excerpts] Mostar has been completely peaceful today. 
[passage omitted] 
  Croatian Defense Council [HVO] formations in the Lasva river 
valley have placed their heavy guns under UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR] supervision at the UN base in Bila, in the 
municipality of Vitez, but HVO military sources said that the 
same action was not taken by Muslim soldiers. The command of 
the HVO Vitez operational zone lodged a protest with UNPROFOR 
because the Muslim side in that area had not placed a single gun 
under UNPROFOR supervision. [passage omitted] 
  Herceg-Bosna Prime Minister Jadranko Prlic and Chamber of 
Deputies President Ivan Bender had talks with French Ambassador 
Henri Jacolin today. In their talks they put forward a demand 
for Mostar not to be placed under European Union administration 
but to be included in the Croat Grand County, with a separate 
Muslim municipality within it. They also put forward a proposal 
by the Croat side that the Croat Grand County be given a land 
link with Herzegovina. 

