<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic Seeks Protection for Srebrenica </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703200894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0703200894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Izetbegovic has sent a letter to the UN 
Security Council regarding the situation in Srebrenica. 
  Srebrenica, which was declared a protected zone by Security 
Council Resolutions 824 and 836, had been quiet for some time. 
However, the Serbian aggressor has recently started attacking 
the town again and is brutally violating the obligations 
contained in these resolutions. 
  Exploiting the changeover of two contingents of peace 
forces, 
Karadzic's Serbs occupied the villages of Tjeskovici, Ursici, 
Jasenovo, and Podravanje on 2, 3, and 4 March. These villages 
are inside the protected zone. On the night of 4-5 March, they 
attacked the camp settlement in Slapovici. The settlement is 
being built with the donations of the Swedish and Norwegian 
Governments. In doing so, they killed and captured a fairly 
large number of civilians. Approximately 1,000 people who moved 
in in the finished part of the settlement were forced to flee 
toward the town. 
  It transpires from the aforementioned facts that the Serbian 
aggressor is continuing to ignore all the decisions of the 
international community. On the other hand, UNPROFOR [United 
Nations Protected Forces] is unable to effectively protect the 
civilian population in the demilitarized zone of Srebrenica. 
  Esteemed sir, we beg you that the Security Council take 
appropriate measures so that the units of Karadzic's Serbs 
withdraw to the previous lines of the protected Srebrenica zone 
and ensure firmer control of the situation on the ground so that 
the refugees could at least be guaranteed elementary safety in 
their settlements. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

