<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic: Maglaj Situation `Critical' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703151494 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0703151494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following the continuation of the Serbian forces' 
offensive on Maglaj, Alija Izetbegovic, president of the 
Presidency of Bosnia-Herzegovina, sent a letter to the chairman 
of the UN Security Council, in which he says the following: 
  The Security Council's Resolution 900 is undoubtedly useful. 
We believe that it will encourage the process of calming the 
armed conflict throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina even more. 
However, it has not yet protected Maglaj, which has been under 
a siege for nine months and has been subjected to a general 
offensive by the Serbian forces in the past month. 
  The aggressor is constantly increasing pressure by 
introducing new weapons withdrawn from around Sarajevo. Several 
tens of thousands of people in the besieged town will not be 
able to put up resistance for much longer against the 
technically incomparably much stronger attacker. 
  The situation is critical and requires an urgent action of 
the Security Council. It is necessary to halt the attacks 
immediately and send international observers and peacekeeping 
troops to the besieged town. Otherwise, there will be another 
genocide. 
  If the international community allows this to happen through 
its passivity, all progress made in the past month would be 
devalued. If, on the other hand, the tragedy of Maglaj is 
prevented with a resolute action, this will give a new impetus 
to the process of establishing peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Esteemed sir, I beg you that the Security Council 
immediately 
adopt a decision appropriate to the gravity of the situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

