<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Deny Bombing Maglaj </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0603154994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1421 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0603154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Banja Luka, 6 Mar (TANJUG) -- Maglaj has not 
been bombed and the so-called army of Bosnia-Herzegovina, in 
line with its common practice, has been setting old tires ablaze 
to create an impression that the town was bombed, the 
information service of the First Krajina Corps of the Serb 
Republic Army said in today's statement in Banja Luka. 
  It is a question of the offensive which the so-called 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army began after the Croat-Muslim agreement 
was signed in Washington. The offensive had also been announced 
on several occasions in the media by the chief of their General 
Staff, Army General Rasim Delic, and the chief of the Supreme 
Command, General Sefer Halilovic. 
  The Serb army statement adds that in the past few days the 
Muslim army stepped up the concentration of its forces from the 
117th Muslim brigade, 208th shock Muslim brigade, and of new 
units brought in from Kakanj to the areas of Gracanica and 
Lukavac. Offensive actions have already started against Ozren, 
Trebava, and Doboj. [passage omitted] 
  The statement also warns of a link between the commands of 
the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army, UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces], 
and also representatives of the EU observer mission staying at 
the Internacional Hotel in Zenica. 

</TEXT>

