<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Claim FRG Refugees To Join Muslim Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0703202094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1833 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0703202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 7 (TANJUG)--Apart from expelling 
Serbs from its territory, Germany is gathering Moslem refugees 
to organize their departure for the ex-Yugoslav Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to join the Bosnian Moslem Army. 
  Citing Bosnian Serb military sources, the news agency of the 
Bosnian Serb Republic (RS)--SRNA, says that the German 
authorities are in this way getting rid of the Moslem refugees 
and, at the same time, enabling the Moslem side to take better 
military positions in the almost two-year civil war in Bosnia. 
  It is clear, a Bosnian Serb military statement said, that 
the 
entire action was completely agreed by Bonn and the Moslem 
authorities in Sarajevo and is carried out in synchronization 
with Bonn's and Washington's efforts to re-establish the 
Moslem-Croat military and diplomatic coalition with unconcealed 
anti-Serb intentions. 
  The Bosnian Croats and Moslems, former allies against the 
Bosnian Serbs, clashed a year ago over territories with a mixed 
population. 
  Last week the two sides met in Washington, at the insistence 
of the United States, and signed a draft agreement on setting up 
a joint federation in Bosnia and a subsequent confederation with 
neighbouring Croatia. 
  On Monday Germany announced it would begin expelling 100,000 
people with Yugoslav passports who are illegally in Germany. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

