<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   President, Defense Minister Trade Accusations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0503220094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2130 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0503220094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ljubljana, March 5 (TANJUG) -- Slovenian Defence 
Minister Janez Jansa accuses President Milan Kucan of running 
illegal para-intelligence services and spy groups, the 
LJUBLJANSKI DNEVNIK daily wrote on Saturday. 
  The accusation comes at a time when the activity of these 
services in this breakaway Yugoslav republic, which has recently 
been made public by Kucan, is being traced back to Jansa's 
ministry. 
  Commenting on Kucan's statement that para-intelligence 
services and spies are keeping under surveillance leading 
Slovenian state officials, prominent citizens and individual 
reporters and are prepared to liquidate them if necessary, Jansa 
told LJUBLJANSKI DNEVNIK that the president "probably has in 
mind the various detective agencies ruled" by members of the 
State Security Service from the Communist times, "most of whom 
he knows personally." The agents were officially subordinated 
to Kucan while he was Slovenia's communist leader, "and are 
today probably unofficially" subordinated to him, averred Jansa. 
  The defence minister for the first time mentioned that he 
has 
received "numerous threats of physical liquidation," but did not 
elaborate. 
  "Liquidation threats should be taken seriously, especially 
after the murder of Ivan Kramberger," killed in the finale of 
the 1992 presidential campaign, said Jansa. 
  The quarrel between Kucan and Jansa, who have traded 
accusations also in a scandal involving arms smuggling for the 
interests of Bosnian Moslems, has been joined by the leadership 
of the United List, the second most influential parliamentary 
party, which has announced its intention to demand the 
resignation or recall of Jansa in the ruling coalition next 
week, on the grounds that "he is unfit for this position of 
authority." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

