<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Redman in Belgrade for Talks With Milosevic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803114294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1056 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0803114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 8 (TANJUG) -- U.S. President Bill 
Clinton's special envoy Charles Redman arrived in Belgrade on 
Tuesday morning and, as it has been learned, is shortly to meet 
with President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia. 
  Redman, it has been learned, has not brought with him any 
concrete proposals, and obviously means only to hear Belgrade's 
position on the U.S. initiative for the creation of a 
Muslim-Croat federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The question of 
the Bosnian Serb side has been left open in that context. 
  An answer has, however, come from Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan 
Karadzic, who has said that "only political illiterates can 
expect the Serbs in Bosnia to accept a confederative model with 
the Muslims and Croats," and who has underscored that only two 
possibilities exist as far as the Bosnian Serbs are concerned -- 
"an independent Serb state in Bosnia or the unification of the 
Bosnian Serbs with the other Serbs into a single state." 
  It is believed that Milosevic and Redman will exchange views 
on the enhancement of the Bosnia-Herzegovina negotiating 
process, which is to produce a comprehensive settlement 
acceptable to all three warring sides in the former Yugoslav 
republic. 
  According to unconfirmed reports, Redman will meet in 
Belgrade also with Vice-President of the Bosnian Serb Republic 
Nikola Koljevic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

