<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economy Faces Worsening Conditions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0703202094 Skopje MILS-NEWS in English 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0703202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MILS-NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Bad Economic Situation"] </F>
  [Text] The economic system in Macedonia [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] is not functioning 
completely, and the parts of it that do function are faced with 
conditions worse than last year's. These are the global 
evaluations of the Macedonian Chamber of Commerce, which is 
following the realization of the 1994 stabilization program of 
the government. The situation in certain segments, as for 
example in the monetary policy, is even worse than last year and 
threaten to prove disastrous for the economy. 
  The companies, besides on the Greek embargo and reduced 
foreign markets, also bitterly criticized the domestic factors 
smothering the realization of the stabilization program. They 
point out the low percentage of using of the available 
capacities, the heavy burden of public expenditures, the low 
accumulative capacity of the economy, and the unemployment. The 
January break of the planned 8 percent to even up to [passage 
indistinct] end of the year is realistic. Therefore, they 
appealed to the bankers not to introduce a rapid increase of the 
interest rates. The restrictive monetary policy threatens to 
grow into a real war between the banks and the companies, since 
it gives little opportunities for the weakened Macedonian 
economy. The companies claim the interest rates are not in the 
function of stabilizing and stimulating the production. 
  Additional problems are also the delayed privatization 
process, the too large exposure of the domestic market to 
liberalization, etc. In such conditions it is hard to expect 
that the economy will function property, and a co-operation 
between the proposer -- the Government and [passage indistinct]. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

