<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ethnic Minorities Discussed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0503190294 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1700 
GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0503190294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Foreign ministers of the Central European 
Initiative [CEI] member states ended their two-day meeting in 
the Italian city of Trieste today. Here is our special 
correspondent Klara Stejskalova with a summary of what happened 
at the conference. 
  [Stejskalova] [passage omitted] Czech Foreign Minister Josef 
Zieleniec emphasized that the Czech Republic is interested in 
deepening cooperation in the area of migration and in 
contributing to the shaping of pan-European migration policy. 
[passage omitted] 
  More controversial was, as usual, the question of ethnic 
minorities, which was brought to a head mainly by the Hungarian 
side. In this connection, Slovak representative Jozef Prokes 
emphasized that the Council of Europe session in Vienna did not 
reach any agreement on ethnic minorities. He reminded of the 
absence of a comparative study of the position of Central 
European minorities, something that is needed for an overall 
solution to this problem. At the same time, he firmly refused 
to accept that this problem is specific to our region. 
  Josef Zieleniec stated his belief that the minority issue -- 
and other political problems -- should be dealt with by 
appropriate bodies, such as the Council of Europe. The CEI 
should rather concentrate on concrete economic cooperation. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

