<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abdic Tells Tudjman of Support for Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0703153394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1400 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0703153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Croatian President Franjo Tudjman received Fikret 
Abdic, member of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency, in the 
presidential palace in Zagreb today. The meeting was also 
attended by Mate Granic, deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister. They discussed the details of the Washington 
agreement and the course of the Vienna negotiations conducted by 
the transition committee for the preparation of a final 
agreement between Croats and Bosnian Muslims on entering a 
federation as two equal and constituent nations and on setting 
up a confederal union with the Republic of Croatia. 
  It was said during the talks that the Vienna negotiations 
are 
expected to end by 15 March, when the final agreement should be 
signed. President Tudjman stressed that the agreement is not 
directed against the third side, but that the Bosnian Serbs are 
invited to join the negotiations. 
  Lending his support to the Washington agreement, Abdic 
stressed that he has always advocated close cooperation between 
the Croat and Muslim nations, and that he opposed the elements 
in the Muslim leadership which fomented Croat-Muslim clashes. 
Abdic particularly stressed the importance of President 
Tudjman's efforts to involve the Serb side in the negotiations 
in order to restore peace. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

