<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel: Moscow `Cannot Decide' for Czech Republic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0703192794 Rome RAI Televideo Teletext in Italian 1734 GMT 
7 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0703192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome RAI Televideo Teletext </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Italian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] There are tones in Russian foreign policy that are 
beginning to cause concern. The Czech Republic wants to enjoy a 
good relationship with Moscow, but "Russia cannot decide on our 
behalf which international organizations we can or cannot join." 
  The statement was made by Czech President Vaclav Havel, who 
was speaking at a news conference in Rome on the Moscow veto on 
any Central and East European country joining NATO. Havel then 
said that the West "had been too slow" in understanding the 
problems of East Europe. Earlier, the Czech president had been 
received by the pope and by President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

